<H1>Printing</H1>

<P>Choose <I>Print...</I> from the <I>Album</I> or <I>Image</I>
menus to display the print dialog and print one or more
images.</P>

<P>Click on the <I>Printer</I> chooser to pick the printer to
use, and check the <I>Print to File</I> box to send the print to
a file instead of the printer.</P>

<P>Click on <I>Print</I> to print the images, <I>Cancel</I> to
cancel printing.</P>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="print-general.jpg" WIDTH="370" HEIGHT="453"
ALT="General Options in the Print Dialog"></CENTER>

<H2><A NAME="general">General Options</A></H2>

<P>The <I>General Options</I> pane controls which images are printed,
how they are formatted on the page, and how many copies are produced.

<H3>Which</H3>

<P>Click on <I>Current Image</I>, <I>Selected Images</I>, or
<I>All Images</I> to choose which images to print.

<H3>Format</H3>

<P>Click on one of the format buttons to print an index, one
image per page, two images per page, four images per page, a
"portrait" collection of each image per page, a calendar with
one image per month, or matted images.

<H3>Copies</H3>

<P>Enter the number of copies you would like of each image. When
printing index, one image per page, or portrait pages, the
copies will be collated. When printing two or four images per
page, the copies may begin in the middle of a page. For example,
when printing four copies of three selected images (A, B, and C)
in the four images per page format, three pages will be printed
with the following images:

<UL>

	<LI>Page 1: A, B, C, and A
	<LI>Page 2: B, C, A, and B
	<LI>Page 3: C, A, B, and C

</UL>

<H3>Quality</H3>

<P>Click on the <I>Quality</I> chooser to pick the output
quality to use. <I>Draft</I> quality will print low-resolution
versions of the images. <I>Normal</I> quality adjusts the image
resolution based on the size of the image on the page.
<I>Best</I> quality always uses the full resolution of each
image.

<H3>Mode</H3>

<P>Click on the <I>Mode</I> chooser to pick whether to print in
grayscale or color.

<CENTER><IMG SRC="print-printer.jpg" WIDTH="471" HEIGHT="438"
ALT="Printer Options in the Print Dialog"></CENTER>

<H2><A NAME="printer">Printer Options</A></H2>

<P>The <I>Printer</I> pane controls the printer and
printer options that are used when printing the images.

<H3>Media Size</H3>

<P>Click on the <I>Media Size</I> chooser to pick the media to use.

<H3>Other Printer Options</H3>

<P>Click on the appropriate chooser to pick other
printer-specific options. The box below the <I>Media Size</I>
fields can be scrolled when the printer driver supplies more
than five extra options.

<CENTER><IMG SRC="print-calendar.jpg" WIDTH="458" HEIGHT="453"
ALT="Calendar Options in the Print Dialog"></CENTER>

<H2><A NAME="calendar">Calendar Options</A></H2>

<P>The <I>Calendar</I> pane controls the starting month and year and
the image position for printed calendar(s).

<H3>Start Day</H3>

<P>Click on the <I>Start Day</I> chooser to select the first day
of the week to print on the calendar. The chooser defaults to
<I>Sunday</I>.

<H3>Start Month</H3>

<P>Click on the <I>Start Month</I> chooser to select the first
month to print as a calendar. The chooser defaults to the
current month.

<H3>Start Year</H3>

<P>Enter the initial year in the <I>Start Year</I> field. The
field defaults to the current year.

<H3>Image Position</H3>

<P>Click on the <I>Left</I>, <I>Top</I>, or <I>Auto</I> buttons
to set the position of the image with respect to the calendar.
The default is Auto which will position landscape images above
the calendar and portrait images to the left of the calendar.

<H3>Type</H3>

<P>Click on the <I>Type</I> chooser to select the type of
calendar to print. The default <I>Single Page</I> calendar type
places a single image and calendar on each page. <I>Bound</I>
calendars are formatted to print a cover image and monthly
calendars for the remaining images that may be bound together;
spiral and comb binders are especially good for this.
<I>Folded</I> calendars are formatted so that the pages can be
stapled and folded in the middle of the pages. Both bound and
folded calendars are meant to be printed on both sides of the
page and offer even/odd page types for printers that don't
support double-sided printing.</P>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="print-matted.jpg" WIDTH="422" HEIGHT="433"
ALT="Matted Images Options in the Print Dialog"></CENTER>

<H2><A NAME="matted">Matted Images Options</A></H2>

<P>The <I>Matted Images</I> pane controls the appearance and
size of matted images.

<H3>Mat Type</H3>

<P>Click on the <I>Mat Type</I> chooser to select a style of matting; the
following mat types are available:

<UL>

	<LI><I>Blank</I>; this mat type leaves blank space around the
	image(s).

	<LI><I>Plain</I>; this mat type draws a flat colored border
	around each image.

	<LI><I>Standard</I>; this mat type draws a colored
	border around each image that is textured to look like a
	standard cardboard matting.

	<LI><I>Velvet</I>; this mat type draws a colored border
	around each image that is textured to look like velvet
	matting.

</UL>

<H3>Mat Width</H3>

<P>Enter the desired width of the matting in the <I>Mat
Width</I> field; click on the chooser to use different units.

<H3>Mat Color</H3>

<P>Enter the desired matting color in the <I>Mat Color</I>
field, click on the <I>Choose...</I> button to display the color
chooser, or click on one of the color tiles to pick the
corresponding color.

<P>The color tiles represent the 16 most common colors in the
image(s) to be printed.

<H3>Image Size</H3>

<P>Enter the desired width and height of the printed image(s).
Images are scaled, rotated, and cropped as needed.

<H3>Image Columns</H3>

<P>Enter the desired number of images to be displayed
horizontally across the page.

<H3>Image Rows</H3>

<P>Enter the desired number of images to be displayed vertically
down the page.

